8–1120","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1097":"1097","1150":"1150","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","La Perche, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"La Perche, Cher, Centre, Frankrijk","Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Amiens, Picardie, França":"Amiens, Picardie, Frankrijk","Amiens, Somme, Picardie, França":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1072–1150":"1072–1150","1072–1136":"1072–1136","1060–Male":"1060–Deceased","1102–Female":"1102–Deceased","1104–Male":"1104–Deceased","1108–1147":"1108–1147","1098–1120":"1098–1120","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1097":"1097","1150":"1150","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","La Perche, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"La Perche, Cher, Centre, France","Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France","Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Amiens, Picardie, França":"Amiens, Picardie, France","Amiens, Somme, Picardie, França":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France","France":"France","Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"D'Ath","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Shashank, Urmila, Ashwini, Chetan, Hari, Medha, Ravi, Santosh, Shashi, Sumit, Vandana, Vijay.  Japanese Masaki, Shiro, Hiroaki, Kazuo, Nobuo, Noriko, Tomoaki, Tsutomu, Yoko, Yoshihiko.","Indian (Maharashtra; pronounced as two syllables): Konkanastha Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>dātā</i> ‘donor’.","Japanese (pronounced as two syllables): written phonetically 伊達 ‘that’ and ‘arrive’. It is a habitational name from a place called Idate in Mutsu (now Aomori) prefecture, borne by a samurai family descended from the northern   Fujiwara   clan."],"variants":[{"name":"Dates","meanings":["(1997: 340;2007: 899; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Date  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Fujiwara","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Makoto, Masataka, Akihiko, Akio, Hideo, Junko, Kazuhiro, Kiyoto, Koji, Miho, Minoru, Toru.","Japanese: written 藤原 ‘wisteria plain’. It is the name of the greatest noble clan of classical Japan. They descend from the statesman Nakatomi no Kamatari (614–669), who was awarded the Fujiwara surname by Emperor Tenji for his part in crushing the powerful   Soga   family and placing Tenji on the throne. <i>Fujiwara</i> is a common placename in Japan. Kamatari's birthplace was Fujiwara in Yamato (in present-day Kashihara-shi, Nara prefecture). The surname is listed in the <i>Shinsen shōjiroku</i>, as is the ancestral name,   Nakatomi  . The family claims descent from Ame no Koyane, a son of the deity Takamimusubi and a companion of the mythical hero Ninigi.","History: Two major branches of the clan are the ‘northern’ and ‘southern’ Fujiwara, named for the relative locations of the mansions of their founders, two grandsons of Fujiwara Kamatari: Muchimaro (680–737; northern) and Fusasaki (682–737; southern). The family rose to greatness during the 10th and 11th centuries by marrying daughters to emperors and other important court figures. The name is no longer common in its original form, but local variants such as <i>Satō</i> (see   Sato  ), <i>Itō</i> (see   Ito  ), <i>Saitō</i> (see   Saito  ), and <i>Katō</i> (see   Kato  ) make the Fujiwara the largest clan in Japan. Many variants of the name were created by taking the first syllable of the name of a family head's residence, or of his official title, and adding to it the suffix <i>-tō</i>, which is the Sino-Japanese reading of the word <i>fuji</i> (‘wisteria’). Thus, for example, the Fujiwara of Sano (<i>Sano no Fujiwara</i>) are called <i>Satō</i>. The name Fujiwara appears in Hawaiian records in the late 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Béatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Béatrix D'Ath was born in 1072, in La Perche, Cher, Centre, France. She married Roger de Arden in 1097, in Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1150, in Amiens, Picardie, France, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1072–1150":"1072–1150","1072–1136":"1072–1136","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1102–Female":"1102–Surnud","1104–Male":"1104–Surnud","1108–1147":"1108–1147","1098–1120":"1098–1120","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1097":"1097","1150":"1150","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","La Perche, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"La Perche, Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa","Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampton in Arden, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France":"Am